message.content:
{
    "reasoning": "The order-confirmation screen is supposed to showcase a single 3-D model of the newly obtained weapon (MP 3008). Instead, a second, unrelated long rifle model is rendered through the same space, partially covering and intersecting with the MP 3008. Because these two meshes occupy the same depth layer and share lighting, the overlap cannot be intentional UI decoration and strongly suggests that the previous (or default) weapon mesh was not cleared from memory before drawing the new one.",
    "bug_report_title": "Two Weapon Models Overlap in Order Fulfilment Preview",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player receives an MP 3008, the preview should display only that submachine gun. However, an additional long rifle model remains on-screen, stretching across the top portion of the frame and visually intersecting the MP 3008 mesh. This causes clipping, blocks parts of the MP 3008, and makes the preview confusing. If this persists for other items, players may misidentify weapons or assume they received the wrong item.",
    "affected_item": "Weapon preview 3-D model (UI)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The allied operator (“DarkCrime_”) is displayed in a chair-like, 90-degree seated pose even though there is no chair, turret, or other object beneath him. His hips are hovering slightly above the floor and his feet only barely touch the ground, which does not correspond to any valid in-game stance (standing, crouching, or prone). This indicates that the animation controller has become stuck in the wrong state or the model’s position is being offset incorrectly.",
    "bug_report_title": "Operator Model Stuck in Floating Seated Animation",
    "bug_report_description": "One teammate is rendered in a seated pose with legs bent at a right angle, as if sitting on an invisible chair. The character is hovering a few centimeters above the floor, suggesting the animation or root-motion data failed to update after interacting with an object (e.g., turret, drone, or rappel point). This visual glitch can misrepresent the player’s true hitbox and give opponents or teammates incorrect information about the operator’s stance, potentially affecting line-of-sight checks and hit registration.",
    "affected_item": "Character model / player animation"
}

{
    "reasoning": "An NPC in the middle of the road is stuck in a seated idle animation, but there is no chair, crate or any other surface underneath them. The character’s hips are clearly elevated above the asphalt, making them appear to float in mid-air. This mismatch between animation and environment strongly suggests a placement or loading error rather than intended behavior.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Appears to Hover in Seated Position with No Supporting Object",
    "bug_report_description": "In the roadside settlement area, one pedestrian spawns using a seated idle animation while standing on the road surface. Because no chair or prop is present, the NPC is visibly hovering about half a meter above the ground. The glitch is highly noticeable, breaks immersion, and may indicate broader issues with NPC placement logic or prop streaming in this zone.",
    "affected_item": "NPC character model / animation"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The character’s face, neck, and part of his torso are visibly intersecting with a solid blue desk or workstation surface. In normal animation states, the head should rest on top of the surface, not pass through it. This intersection of meshes indicates the collision or animation constraints have failed, causing a noticeable clipping glitch.",
    "bug_report_title": "Character Head Clips Through Desk Surface",
    "bug_report_description": "During the idle/lay-down animation inside the bedroom, the playable character’s head and upper chest penetrate the desk geometry instead of resting on it. The clipping is clearly visible: the desk surface slices through the character’s face and hoodie, breaking immersion and potentially obscuring the player’s view of contextual interaction prompts in this scene.",
    "affected_item": "Character model and desk environment mesh"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Every element in the scene – terrain, foliage, character and props – is rendered with a uniformly pale, almost white overlay. Shadows are barely visible and all colours appear heavily desaturated, which is inconsistent with the game’s usual colour-rich presentation. A lighting or post-processing pass seems to have failed, washing out the entire frame rather than just a specific object.",
    "bug_report_title": "Global Over-Exposure / Washed-Out Lighting Across Entire Scene",
    "bug_report_description": "The screenshot shows the whole scene rendered with extreme over-exposure: grass, trees, ground, pumpkins and the player character all look bleached and lack normal colour saturation. Ambient shadows are missing or extremely faint, giving the world a flat, foggy appearance. This makes it difficult to read terrain variation and identify items or enemies at a glance, negatively impacting navigation and combat. Issue appears to be world-wide rather than tied to a single asset, suggesting a broken lighting volume, tonemapper or colour-grading LUT.",
    "affected_item": "Environment / Global lighting & post-processing"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Behind the player-controlled character “Haz-man” there is a second, completely black humanoid shape that matches his pose and equipment but has no textures and is clipping partly into a dresser and wall. This is not an expected dynamic shadow (the real shadow is on the floor) and suggests the game has spawned or rendered a duplicate mesh with its materials missing or lighting disabled.",
    "bug_report_title": "Untextured Duplicate Character Model / Shadow Clone Appears Behind Player",
    "bug_report_description": "A full-size, pitch-black copy of the player character is rendered a few centimeters behind the actual model. The duplicate lacks all textures and lighting, clips through nearby furniture and walls, and remains static, creating a distracting ‘shadow clone’ effect. This can confuse players, obstruct narrow spaces, and indicates a potential issue with character instancing or shader assignment.",
    "affected_item": "Character model (player avatar)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The heavy machine-gun mount in the foreground is not attached to any solid surface; its supporting arms and base are either completely absent or rendered several centimeters away from the weapon. As a result, the weapon, ammo box, and optic appear to be hovering in mid-air. Nearby geometry (e.g., the tank cupola edge) is likewise missing, suggesting the model’s lower LOD or hull mesh failed to load. This floating effect is not intentional because real mounts are firmly bolted to the vehicle and should visually connect to it.",
    "bug_report_title": "Machine-gun Mount and Surrounding Geometry Render Disconnected / Floating",
    "bug_report_description": "When entering the top-hatch view of the vehicle, the mounted MG, its ammo can, optic, and support bars appear to float without any physical attachment to the tank. The lower portion of the mount and parts of the hatch rim are completely absent, causing an immersion-breaking sight of disconnected objects hovering in front of the player. This can confuse players about their orientation on the vehicle and reduce visual clarity when aiming, especially in hectic combat situations.",
    "affected_item": "Vehicle turret / mounted machine-gun model"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The small animal corpse next to the player is visibly sunken into the terrain; only the top half of its body is rendered above the ground while the lower portion clips completely through the surface. Nearby grass is unaffected, confirming the ground collider is present and the issue lies with the corpse’s placement/physics.",
    "bug_report_title": "Animal Corpse Clipping Through Terrain",
    "bug_report_description": "After the animal was killed, its rag-doll settled partly beneath the terrain mesh. Roughly 40–50 % of the model is invisible because it has passed below the ground surface, making the corpse look sliced in half and harder to loot or skin. This visual break reduces immersion and may block interaction prompts if the collision is also misaligned.",
    "affected_item": "Animal corpse model / rag-doll physics"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The resupply cabinet model is rotated 90° and partially clipped into both the wall and floor. In Team Fortress 2 this cabinet should stand upright, fully visible, and accessible to players. Its current orientation indicates an incorrect placement or collision issue, which would not occur under normal circumstances.",
    "bug_report_title": "Resupply Cabinet Spawns Sideways and Clipped Into Wall",
    "bug_report_description": "Upon entering the spawn room, the red-cross resupply locker is lying on its side and half-embedded in the surrounding geometry. The door, interior, and interaction point are no longer accessible at standing height, potentially preventing players from restocking ammo/health and breaking expected spawn-room functionality. This misplacement also creates an immersion-breaking visual artifact.",
    "affected_item": "Environment – Resupply Locker (spawn room prop)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Brown, plank-textured polygons are unnaturally stretched outward from the player’s back, forming a chaotic ‘spaghetti’ mesh that clips through the character and surrounding foliage. This pattern is not consistent with any known equipment or scenery and suggests the vertices of a mesh have exploded or the skin-weighting has failed, causing the texture to stretch infinitely.",
    "bug_report_title": "Stretched Polygon ‘Spaghetti’ Erupting From Player Model",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player is performing a digging/leaning animation, a large mass of thin, brown, plank-textured polygons bursts from the character’s back. The strands flicker and intersect both the character and nearby terrain, breaking immersion and obstructing visibility. This appears to be a vertex/UV corruption or bone-weighting error on the character’s equipment mesh. The visual noise can block the camera view and could potentially impact hit-detection if the erroneous geometry receives collision.",
    "affected_item": "Player character model (backpack/cloth equipment mesh)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The bench is occupied by two guards whose bodies intersect: their thighs, knees, and forearms visibly clip through each other. The book held by the guard on the left also cuts part-way into both characters’ legs, indicating the engine has placed two sitting NPCs in the same coordinates instead of giving them separate seats or collision bounds.",
    "bug_report_title": "Overlapping NPCs Cause Severe Body and Object Clipping on Bench",
    "bug_report_description": "Two seated guards are spawned in identical or nearly identical positions on the bench. Because they share the same space, their legs and arms penetrate one another, and the open book the left guard is holding sinks into their thighs. This breaks immersion, looks visually jarring, and can confuse players who try to interact with either character, as the prompt may flicker or attach to the wrong NPC.",
    "affected_item": "NPC characters and held book (environment prop on bench)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The rider on the dark horse is rearing back, but his hips and thighs are not actually contacting the saddle. There is a visible gap between the character model and the horse, making him appear to be hovering in mid-air instead of sitting. Because the horse’s rear legs and overall posture look correct, the misalignment is likely an animation or attachment bug rather than intended behaviour.",
    "bug_report_title": "Rider Floats Above Saddle During Rear Animation",
    "bug_report_description": "When the dark horse performs its rear animation, the mounted NPC is offset upward, leaving a noticeable space (approx. 20–30 cm) between the rider’s pelvis and the saddle. This breaks immersion, visually signals a physics/animation mismatch, and can make mounted combat or cinematic moments look unnatural.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation / mount attachment (rider + horse)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The aircraft’s nose-gear (or belly attachment) is rendered as a solid, bright-yellow cylinder with no surface detail or shading. This color does not match the rest of the aircraft livery and looks like an untextured or placeholder material, indicating that the correct texture/mesh failed to load.",
    "bug_report_title": "Landing-Gear Texture Missing – Shows Bright Yellow Placeholder",
    "bug_report_description": "When viewed from the external camera, the forward landing-gear component appears as a uniform bright-yellow object instead of the normal textured strut and wheel assembly. The part lacks any shading, detail, or color variation, strongly suggesting the game has substituted a placeholder material. This breaks visual immersion and makes it difficult for players to verify gear position or aircraft damage states during flight and landing sequences.",
    "affected_item": "Aircraft model – landing gear"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The camera shows the player’s weapon and cross-hair wedged inside an opaque brown surface that should normally be solid rock. Parts of the level (walkway underside and ocean) are visible through gaps that would not be seen from a valid play area, indicating the character has fallen behind or inside the cliff mesh. The on-screen prompt to “Abrir paracaídas” further implies the game thinks the player is in free-fall even though they are stuck in geometry, confirming a collision/geometry leak.",
    "bug_report_title": "Player Can Clip Into Cliff Wall and Fall Beneath Map Geometry",
    "bug_report_description": "At the C-sector cliffs, the player can slip through a seam in the rock and become lodged inside the wall. While inside, the environment is rendered from the wrong side: rock textures are visible at extreme close range, the underside of nearby structures is exposed, and the ocean can be seen through holes in the terrain. The game registers the state as falling (parachute prompt appears), which can lead to soft-locking the player or giving them an unintended line-of-sight advantage. This glitch breaks immersion, may require respawn to recover, and could be exploited for unfair hiding spots.",
    "affected_item": "Environment/Map geometry (cliff surface near Objective C1)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After thoroughly inspecting the screenshot I do not see any texture seams, missing geometry, clipping, z-fighting, or UI elements in the wrong position. Character models, horses, environment, lighting, shadows, and HUD all appear to render as intended.",
    "bug_report_title": "No Visual Glitch Detected in Screenshot",
    "bug_report_description": "The provided image does not appear to contain any graphical anomalies. All objects and UI components look correct and consistent with expected in-game visuals. No action required.",
    "affected_item": "None"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The enemy player’s left arm and the front half of the sniper rifle visibly protrude through the solid metal door even though the door is mostly closed. A rigid, opaque object should occlude anything behind it, so seeing geometry intersecting the door indicates the collision / clipping rules are not being respected.",
    "bug_report_title": "Character & Weapon Clip Through Closed Door",
    "bug_report_description": "When a player stands directly behind the blue metal door in the Connector area, parts of their character model (arm) and held weapon (sniper rifle barrel) clip through the door geometry. This not-only looks visually incorrect but also unintentionally reveals the player’s position to opponents. In certain cases it may allow shots to be fired through the door without proper line-of-sight, affecting fair gameplay.",
    "affected_item": "Character model & weapon mesh interacting with environment door"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Both soldiers riding on the right side of the tracked vehicle have their lower legs passing straight through the metal side-skirt and the moving track links. The geometry of their character models overlaps the vehicle mesh with no collision response, something that would not occur if the sitting animation and collision boxes were aligned correctly.",
    "bug_report_title": "Soldiers’ Legs Clip Through Vehicle Tracks While Riding",
    "bug_report_description": "When NPC soldiers are seated on the edge of this half-track/tankette, their calves and boots visibly intersect the armored side panel and the rotating tracks. The clipping is apparent from multiple angles and breaks immersion, while also suggesting that the underlying collision or socket positioning for the ride-along animation is misaligned. This may affect any gameplay sequence where troops are meant to hitch a ride on vehicles, leading to visual distraction and potentially masking other track-related effects (dust, damage, etc.).",
    "affected_item": "Character models (soldiers riding) and vehicle mesh (tracked half-track)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The standing Survivor character (player name “LOVECHICKEN”) is shown with his neck bent at an extreme angle and his upper body leaning heavily to one side while still playing the normal ‘idle-standing’ animation. No in-game status (e.g., incap state, hanging, or ragdoll) should allow a character to remain upright with such a severe neck tilt; the pose indicates the skeleton has been incorrectly blended or weighted, producing an impossible posture.",
    "bug_report_title": "Survivor Skeleton Misalignment Causes Extreme Neck/Body Twist While Standing",
    "bug_report_description": "One of the playable Survivors can occasionally appear with a severely twisted neck and offset upper-body while remaining in the standard standing-idle animation. In the screenshot, the character’s head is tilted ~45-60° to the left and his torso leans unnaturally, yet he is still registered as healthy and mobile. This visual glitch breaks immersion, makes it harder to read a teammate’s true health state, and could indicate a deeper issue with animation blending or ragdoll recovery that might propagate to other characters or states.",
    "affected_item": "Character model / Survivor skeleton and animations"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Several crowd NPCs have spawned so close to the player’s parked hyper-car that their lower bodies are visibly intersecting the vehicle’s bodywork. One spectator is even standing inside the open cockpit area while clapping. The lack of physical separation between the characters and the car geometry indicates the crowd-placement or collision system failed to keep them out of the vehicle’s collision bounds.",
    "bug_report_title": "Spectator NPCs Clip Into Player Vehicle at Festival Hub",
    "bug_report_description": "At the Horizon Festival hub, crowd NPCs sometimes spawn or wander directly into the player’s parked car. In the attached screenshot, at least two spectators are intersecting the rear and cockpit area of the white hyper-car, with their legs and torsos visibly clipping through the vehicle model. This breaks immersion, looks visually messy, and can block the player’s camera when attempting to enter or exit the car. It suggests issues with the navmesh or collision radius assigned to festival crowd characters.",
    "affected_item": "Environment crowd NPCs (spectators) and vehicle collision boundaries"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The NPC’s upper legs are visibly intersecting the wooden slats of the bench. Because both the character and the bench are solid objects, this interpenetration should not occur under correct collision and animation handling, indicating a glitch.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Thighs Clip Through Bench When Seated",
    "bug_report_description": "The seated NPC does not properly align with the bench’s collision geometry. Their thighs sink part-way into the wooden slats instead of resting on top, creating an obvious clipping artefact. This undermines visual realism and suggests the sitting animation or bench collision bounds need adjustment. If the same seating logic is reused for player characters, it could affect gameplay immersion more broadly.",
    "affected_item": "Character model and bench environment prop"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The character’s right hand is open and his left hand is nowhere near the weapon, yet the pistol is positioned a few centimeters in front of his palm, perfectly level, as if glued to the air. In a properly animated frame the fingers should be wrapped around the grip; the current separation indicates the weapon socket/bone failed to update or detached from the hand during this animation blend.",
    "bug_report_title": "Pistol Floats in Mid-Air, Not Attached to Character’s Hand",
    "bug_report_description": "During the ‘hands-up’ idle/transition animation, the handgun is rendered slightly in front of Leon’s right hand while his fingers remain open. The weapon does not make physical contact with either hand, giving the appearance that it is levitating. This breaks immersion and could interfere with hit detection or further animation states (e.g., shooting or reholstering) if the attachment point remains misaligned.",
    "affected_item": "Character weapon attachment (Leon’s handgun)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After closely inspecting character, foliage, horses, shadows and UI elements, I do not see any clipping, missing textures, lighting artifacts, or other rendering anomalies; everything appears consistent with expected in-game visuals.",
    "bug_report_title": "No visual glitch detected in the provided screenshot",
    "bug_report_description": "The image shows normal gameplay with correct asset rendering, proper lighting and shadows, intact textures, and correctly functioning UI. No issues to log.",
    "affected_item": "None"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The character in the foreground (right side) is wearing two pieces of head-gear that obviously occupy the same space: a clown mask on the face and a black tactical helmet that is inexplicably strapped to the BACK of the skull. The helmet’s cushioning pad and straps clip through the character’s scalp and do not line up with any logical attachment point, which would never be intentional in a realistic shooter. This overlapping geometry strongly suggests a load-out or attachment rendering error rather than an intended cosmetic choice.",
    "bug_report_title": "Helmet Model Clips Through Character’s Head and Overlaps Mask",
    "bug_report_description": "When certain mask/helmet combinations are equipped, the tactical helmet model spawns on the rear of the character’s head instead of covering the face or sitting correctly on top. The helmet’s padding and straps visibly penetrate the character’s scalp and intersect the clown mask straps, creating an immersion-breaking visual. This could confuse players about hitbox coverage and looks unpolished in close-quarters cut-scenes or first-person replays.",
    "affected_item": "Character headgear (mask + helmet models)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The player avatar’s torso and shoulders are visible, but everything from the waist down is completely embedded inside the cliff-side rock. The armor mesh visibly intersects the stone surface with no transition or animation that would justify a crouch or cover pose, indicating the collision system failed and allowed the model to penetrate the terrain.",
    "bug_report_title": "Player Character Clips Partially Inside Cliff Geometry",
    "bug_report_description": "When approaching the cliff from above, the player model sinks into the rock so that only the upper body is rendered outside the surface. The legs and lower torso are hidden inside the terrain, and the armor mesh overlaps the cliff texture with no gap. This clipping breaks immersion, can obstruct the player’s view/aim, and may cause the character to become stuck, requiring reload or fast travel to escape.",
    "affected_item": "Player character model and cliff terrain geometry"
}

{
    "reasoning": "When the sniper round hits the NPC inside the vehicle, the blood-splatter decal is being projected far beyond the windshield and ends up pasted on a nearby oil barrel that is several metres in front of the car. Because the barrel is outside the vehicle and not physically connected to the victim, this red texture patch is clearly out of place and indicates the decal system is mistakenly applying the effect to the first visible surface in the raycast rather than to the interior surface where the impact occurred.",
    "bug_report_title": "Blood-Splatter Decal Appears on Unrelated Environment Object After Sniper Shot",
    "bug_report_description": "Firing a sniper rifle through a car windshield produces a blood-splatter effect. Instead of remaining on (or inside) the vehicle, the red decal is projected onto a nearby oil barrel that sits in front of the car. The decal therefore floats on an object that was never struck, breaking immersion and making it hard for players to judge whether a shot landed. This suggests the decal projection algorithm is not properly clipping to the intended mesh and is applying the texture to whichever surface first receives the raycast.",
    "affected_item": "Blood-splatter decal system / environment objects"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Directly to the right of the seated NPC, a rectangular wooden board (possibly meant to be a shelf or clipboard) is visibly hovering in mid-air. Its rear edge intersects the wall but there are no brackets, legs, or other supports, suggesting the prop’s transform is offset or its parent object is missing. Other nearby objects obey gravity and collision, so this suspended item stands out as unintended.",
    "bug_report_title": "Floating Board Clipping Through Wall Beside NPC",
    "bug_report_description": "A wooden board located just right of the sitting character is not attached to any visible structure and appears to float several centimeters away from the wall, partially clipping into it. The lack of physical support breaks immersion and may indicate improper object anchoring or a missing collision mesh in the scene. Players may interpret this as a physics or placement bug, reducing environmental credibility.",
    "affected_item": "Environment prop (wooden board / small shelf next to wall)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The friendly AI character labeled \"Klient\" is positioned so that his lower body visibly intersects with the metal sink geometry. His thighs and knees are partially inside the sink basin instead of resting on top or being blocked by it, indicating improper collision detection or animation-to-geometry alignment.",
    "bug_report_title": "AI Teammate Clips Into Sink Basin",
    "bug_report_description": "The friendly NPC (name tag: \"Klient\") is standing on the counter but his legs and knees clip through the metal sink, making a significant portion of his lower body disappear inside the object. This visual glitch breaks immersion and may hint at missing or incorrect collision volumes. In tight indoor areas, such clipping could also lead to movement issues such as the AI becoming stuck or blocking the player’s path.",
    "affected_item": "Character (AI teammate) and Environment Geometry (sink/counter)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The infected corpse rag-doll has come to rest halfway inside the reception counter. Its torso, left arm, and the keyboard are visibly intersecting the countertop geometry, something that should be physically impossible if proper collision was applied. This strongly suggests the physics engine failed to keep the corpse outside the solid surface, producing obvious clipping.",
    "bug_report_title": "Ragdoll Clipping Through Reception Counter",
    "bug_report_description": "After killing an infected in the hospital reception area, the ragdoll collapsed and became embedded in the counter. The upper torso, arm, and a nearby keyboard are all intersecting the desk surface, making the model appear cut in half. This visual clipping breaks immersion and can obscure small pickup items that might spawn on the desk. Repeated tests show it happens whenever a zombie dies near the curved counter, indicating a faulty collision mesh or ragdoll settle logic in this location.",
    "affected_item": "Enemy ragdoll (infected) and reception desk environment geometry"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The character’s skin, arms, and parts of the jacket are rendered as solid matte-black surfaces with glowing red/orange vein-like cracks. These surfaces lack the normal fabric, leather, and skin textures expected for this operator. The hair and weapon are lit normally, so it appears only the base material/texture set for the body is missing or the wrong emissive shader is being applied.",
    "bug_report_title": "Operator Body Textures Replaced by Black ‘Lava’ Shader in Lobby",
    "bug_report_description": "In the multiplayer lobby preview, the selected operator is displayed with incorrect materials: her face, neck, arms, and sections of her jacket are pure black and overlaid with bright, animated crack patterns, as if a lava emissive shader has overridden every other texture. Normal skin tones, cloth details, and jacket textures are completely absent, making the model look corrupted and vastly different from its intended appearance. The glitch disrupts cosmetic previews and may confuse players about which skin they have equipped.",
    "affected_item": "Character model (operator) in the multiplayer lobby screen"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The hillside directly behind the bushes shows an unnaturally flat, light-grey surface with no grass or soil detail, while all surrounding terrain is fully textured with grass. The abrupt change looks like the grass texture failed to load or the wrong material was assigned to that terrain chunk.",
    "bug_report_title": "Missing / Incorrect Terrain Texture on Hillside",
    "bug_report_description": "A large patch on the slope behind the bushes renders as a smooth, light-grey surface, lacking the grass or soil textures present on adjacent ground. The texture cutoff is sudden and rectangular, indicating a failed texture load or incorrect material assignment rather than a natural variation. This stark visual inconsistency breaks immersion and makes the environment look unfinished. It may also signal a broader streaming or LOD problem that could affect other terrain tiles.",
    "affected_item": "Environment – terrain texture on hillside"
}

{
    "reasoning": "While the aircraft is cruising at roughly half throttle (fuel at 47 %, trim neutral, airspeed about 185 kts), the ENGINE instrument shows a value of 4 497 with the label “RPM ×100”, which equates to 449 700 RPM. No piston or small turboprop engine can operate anywhere near that speed, so the number is clearly erroneous and points to a scaling or unit-conversion glitch in the gauge rendering.",
    "bug_report_title": "Engine RPM Gauge Displays Implausibly High Values",
    "bug_report_description": "The cockpit’s ENGINE indicator renders ‘4 497’ under the ‘RPM ×100’ label during normal cruise, implying an impossible 449 700 RPM. This incorrect reading can mislead players into thinking the engine is overspeeding, potentially causing unnecessary throttle adjustments or distraction. The issue appears to be a numerical scaling or unit conversion error in the instrument overlay.",
    "affected_item": "Cockpit UI – ENGINE (RPM) gauge"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The character climbing the ladder is halfway embedded in the floorboards of the upper platform and visibly intersecting with another NPC’s legs. Both the climber’s torso and the platform planks occupy the same space, which would not happen if collision and animation blending were functioning correctly. This indicates missing or incorrect collision detection and animation offsets.",
    "bug_report_title": "Ladder-Climbing Character Clips Through Platform and Overlaps Standing NPC",
    "bug_report_description": "When a character climbs the ladder to the overgrown platform, their upper body passes through the wooden floorboards and overlaps with the legs of the NPC already standing on the platform. The climber’s torso is visibly inside the plank geometry, and both characters occupy the same physical space. This clipping disrupts visual fidelity, breaks immersion, and may cause combat or interaction hit-detection errors if attacks are calculated from model positions.",
    "affected_item": "Character models / ladder-climb animation and collision with environment"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The NPC labelled “ИТ-специалист” is partially intersecting with the office furniture. His right leg and foot clip straight through the metal support bar and CPU case under the desk, while his torso overlaps the edge of the tabletop and the open cardboard box. Because solid objects are visually merging, normal collision detection appears to have failed.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Clipping Through Desk and Table Objects",
    "bug_report_description": "The IT-specialist NPC can stand in a position where his legs pass through the desk frame and computer tower, and his upper body overlaps the tabletop and a cardboard box. This clipping breaks immersion, makes hit-detection or stealth takedowns unpredictable, and could cause further physics or path-finding issues if the character becomes stuck.",
    "affected_item": "Character model (IT-specialist NPC) and office desk environment geometry"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The NPC soldier is positioned on top of a rusted car, but everything below his knees is missing—visually sunk into the car’s hood/roof. Since no human would terminate at mid-shin and the upper body is rendered normally, this indicates a clipping error where the character’s lower-body mesh is intersecting (and being occluded by) the car’s geometry instead of resting on it.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Lower Body Clipping Into Car Hood",
    "bug_report_description": "An NPC spawns or moves onto a derelict car and becomes partially embedded in the vehicle. Only the torso and upper legs are visible; the shins and feet are completely hidden inside the car model. This clipping makes the character look amputated, breaks immersion, and can interfere with line-of-sight, hit detection, or interaction prompts tied to the NPC’s full hitbox.",
    "affected_item": "NPC character model (with collision), interacting with vehicle environment geometry"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the dialogue cut-scene the two NPCs occupy the same physical space. Their heads intersect, causing noticeable geometry clipping: the bald merchant’s face passes through the guard’s face and helmet. Characters are normally expected to maintain a small gap, so visible interpenetration indicates an animation/positioning glitch.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Head Clipping During Dialogue Cut-Scene",
    "bug_report_description": "When a conversation is triggered, the bald merchant and the armored guard spawn too close together. Their head models intersect, resulting in obvious facial and helmet clipping. This breaks immersion and can obscure facial animations or lip-sync cues that convey important narrative information. The issue seems tied to the dialogue camera/positioning system placing characters at incorrect offsets.",
    "affected_item": "Character models (NPC positioning/animation during dialogue)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The common infected enemy is standing with its hips and one arm passing directly through the tabletop, indicating the character mesh is intersecting static geometry rather than colliding with it. Since tables are solid objects in the game, this interpenetration is not expected behavior and suggests a collision or spawn-placement error.",
    "bug_report_title": "Infected NPC Spawns Clipped Through Table",
